# Cognitive Load Theory {#cognitive-load}

Cognitive load theory, developed by John Sweller[^sweller1988], describes the mental effort required to process information.

## Types of Cognitive Load

Intrinsic load
: The inherent difficulty of the material itself

Extraneous load
: Load caused by poor instructional design

Germane load
: Load devoted to building mental schemas

## Connection to Software Design

Software complexity is directly related to cognitive load[^complexity]. Clean code practices reduce **extraneous load** by making code easier to parse visually.

See [[Clean Code Principles]] and [[Software Complexity Metrics]].

This connects to the idea of ==chunking==[^miller1956] -- grouping information into meaningful units reduces working memory demands.

## Implications for API Design

> Good API design minimizes the cognitive load on the consumer. Every unnecessary option, parameter, or configuration point adds to the burden.

N> This principle applies equally to CLI tools and library interfaces.

[^sweller1988]: Sweller, J. (1988). Cognitive load during problem solving.
[^complexity]: See the discussion in [[Accidental vs Essential Complexity]].
[^miller1956]: Miller, G.A. (1956). The magical number seven, plus or minus two.
